            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lin Wong, 47, grew up in a warm but modest household in the Outer Sunset, the middle child of three. Her parents, immigrants from Hong Kong, ran a small but bustling dry cleaners, instilling in Mei a deep appreciation for hard work and meticulous attention to detail. Weekends were often spent helping out, the rhythmic whir of the machines a constant soundtrack to her childhood. It was during quiet moments in the back, leafing through discarded magazines and dusty books from the local library, that Mei discovered her fascination with history and aesthetics.\n\nHer intellectual curiosity led her to UC Berkeley, where she initially pursued a more practical degree, swayed by her parents' hopes for stability. However, a transformative art history seminar on the Tang Dynasty shifted her trajectory entirely. She pursued a graduate degree, delving deep into the intricacies of Asian art, finding unexpected parallels between the ancient crafts and the careful precision of her parents\u2019 work.\n\nHer career path wasn't linear. After interning at several museums, she landed an entry-level position at a respected institution, starting with administrative tasks and slowly working her way up. A key turning point came when she proposed and successfully executed an exhibition on overlooked female artists from the Cantonese diaspora, earning her recognition and a promotion to Senior Curator. Her current role involves managing complex collections and leading research initiatives, a demanding but deeply fulfilling pursuit.\n\nMei\u2019s personal life is centered around close-knit relationships. She remains incredibly close to her parents, visiting them every Sunday for dim sum in the Richmond. Her social circle consists of a few trusted friends from university and colleagues who share her passion for the arts. She is a supportive aunt to her younger sister's two teenage children, often taking them to museums and galleries.\n\nHer hopes for the future include continuing to bring underrepresented stories to light through her curation and perhaps, one day, authoring a book on a specific area of Asian art. She dreams of securing a significant grant to fund a major international exhibition.\n\nMei\u2019s daily routine is a blend of professional rigor and quiet comfort. The 2.8-mile Muni bus commute through familiar San Francisco streets provides her with a quiet space to read or simply observe the city. Evenings are often spent attending lectures, researching, or enjoying a quiet meal at her favorite neighborhood noodle shop near her apartment in NOPA. San Francisco, with its vibrant cultural scene and diverse communities, feels intrinsically connected to her identity and her work. Her neighborhood, with its blend of independent businesses and established institutions, feels like a microcosm of the city she loves."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The smell of starch and pressing, the rhythmic hiss of the iron \u2013 this was her childhood soundtrack. Folding a tiny child's shirt perfectly, seeing her father\u2019s approving nod; she learned that careful precision applied to beauty, not just clean clothes. That quiet focus shaped her meticulous nature. (Early childhood)\n\n2. Sitting in that dim UC Berkeley lecture hall, the slides of intricate Tang Dynasty pottery filling the screen. A jolt of recognition, a bridge between ancient craftsmanship and her parents\u2019 hands. It felt like finding a hidden language, validating her artistic leanings against practical pressures. (Early twenties)\n\n3. Submitting her proposal for the Cantonese diaspora exhibition, heart pounding. The relief and joy when it was approved, seeing the overlooked artists' work finally given its due. It solidified her belief in bringing hidden narratives to light, a purpose she fiercely protects. (Mid-thirties)\n\n4. Watching her niece, wide-eyed, point at a Ming Dynasty vase during a museum visit. Sharing her passion, seeing a flicker of curiosity in young eyes. It was like passing on a legacy, connecting generations through the stillness and beauty of history. (Present day, within the last few years)\n\n5. Sunday dim sum with her parents, the noisy comfort of conversations in Cantonese and English. The warmth of family, the shared plates, a constant anchor in her life. It reminds her of where she came from, grounding her ambitious career goals in enduring love and connection. (Ongoing, a weekly ritual)"
